Dear Professor Li, 

Hello. Regarding the academic conference in Shanghai next week, I have already completed the registration and payment on the official website. I would like to confirm with you whether the department requires me to prepare a sharing report after the conference. If so, I will prepare the materials in advance.

Okay, Xiaowen, thank you for your hard work. A post-meeting sharing session is necessary. Please pay attention to the cutting-edge content during the conference and prepare a 15-minute sharing session when you return. We will finalize the specific arrangements once you're back.

Sister Qin, I'm so happy for you! I'm definitely available to be your bridesmaid! I just checked my schedule, and I'm on duty on the 2nd and 5th during the National Day week. What's the exact date of the wedding? I'll try to coordinate my leave as soon as possible.

The wedding is scheduled for October 3rd! It's wonderful that you can be a bridesmaid! The timing should work out, so try to adjust your schedule as much as possible. I'll send you the styles of the bridesmaid dresses later for you to choose from.

Jingjing, my stomach is feeling much better. I just had some porridge and steamed egg custard for dinner. The probiotic brand you recommended seems to be working fine for me. How have you been lately?
Mom, I have the early shift tomorrow and have already packed everything. My stomach feels much better today, so please don't worry. Take care of yourselves, both you and Dad.

【XX Bank】Dear customer, your credit card ending with 5678 has generated the current statement. The repayment due date is August 10th, and the amount due is 1,256.78 yuan. You can log in to the mobile banking app to check the details.

Mom, I have a follow-up appointment at the hospital this afternoon. The doctor said my condition has improved, but I still need to continue taking medication and paying attention to my diet. You and Dad should also take care of your health at home. It's been hot lately, so make sure to drink plenty of water.
Mom, I just got back from the hospital. The doctor prescribed some medicine and said it's nothing serious, so don't worry. I'll video call you tonight to explain in detail.

Director Zhang, the progress notes and medical orders for this afternoon have all been updated. Regarding the adverse event report from the conflict this morning, I have submitted it to the hospital system as per the procedure and attached my personal reflection. Please review it at your convenience.

Jingjing, I'm home and just finished dinner. Something happened at the department today, and I'm feeling a bit unsettled. I'd like to talk to you tonight if you're available.
Brother Feng, I encountered some challenges at work today, but I've managed to handle them all. How have you been doing in Shenzhen lately? Is the project going smoothly?
Mom, I checked the weather forecast last night and it said it might rain in Zhengzhou today. Please remember to take an umbrella when you and Dad go out to buy groceries, so you don't get wet.
Teacher Li, I have finished organizing the afternoon documents and reflection notes and have sent them to your email. Please review them when you have time.
Wang Fang, while organizing the documents this afternoon, I noticed a data point in the discharge summary for bed 3 that needs to be verified with you. Please check WeChat when it's convenient.

Jingjing, my gastroenteritis has recovered, and I resumed Pilates tonight! I feel like my body has come back to life. I'm planning to start raising a cat this weekend, would you like to come and take a look?
Teacher Li, I have compiled the notes from this afternoon's professional learning session on non-invasive ventilation parameters and sent them to your email. Please review them when you have time.
Mom, I'm home from work. Coal Ball is doing well—he ate his cat food and used the litter box, but he's still a bit shy and hiding. What did you and Dad have for dinner?

Mom, I'm home. I just refilled Meiqiu's food and water, and the little one is full of energy. For dinner, I ordered a salad and some porridge—keeping it light. Have you and Dad eaten yet?
Mom and Dad, I've sent the PPT to Teacher Li, and it feels pretty good. I'll show you Meiqiu's new look during our video call later. He's been extra clingy today.

Yaya, I continued refining the pottery piece about 'resilience of life' tonight. I just added some texture with a carving knife, and it feels more layered now. Sending you a photo to show you the effect!

What a great photo! The texture is so delicate, and the theme really stands out. There's a pottery throwing workshop at Sesame Street Studio next Sunday afternoon. Would you like to join me? I've already booked a session with Master Zheng for guidance.
Jingjing, I just finished doing yoga and my shoulders and neck feel much better. How have your shoulders and neck been lately? Do you want to go for a massage together this weekend to relax?
Mom and Dad, I'm making tomato and egg noodles for lunch, and we'll probably eat around 11:30. Have you prepared your lunch over there? Let's have a video chat after we finish eating.
Mom, I just got back home from the pottery studio. I installed a new scratching post for Meiqiu, and it's having a blast playing with it.

Jingjing, I really enjoyed our chat tonight. Thank you for listening to me vent. I've started working on my financial planning since I got home. You should get some rest early too, and don't be late for work tomorrow.
Mom, I've just left the hospital apartment by car and should be home in about half an hour. Are you having lunch at home? Do you want me to pick up some groceries on the way back?
Mom, I've finished dinner with Sun Yue, and now I'm taking a walk to help with digestion. What did you and Dad have for dinner? Everything is fine on my end, no need to worry.

Today, while reading, I came across a passage describing the waiting period before surgery, and it really struck a chord with me. It made me realize that being a doctor truly requires a strong heart. You should also rest early. Goodnight.

Jingjing, I've looked at a few fusion restaurants, and they all have nice atmospheres. I'll send you the links to check out. Also, do you prefer fruit cake or cream cake?
Dad, Mom, the dumplings are ready, and I'm all set here too. Let's video call at 6 PM sharp!
I think the private room at 'Chunxi Bistro' is quite nice—it offers good privacy and the food receives high ratings. Shall we book the room before noon tomorrow?

Hello, foreign teacher. Today's oral class simulated an international conference presentation on the progress in the diagnosis and treatment of community-acquired pneumonia. I gained a lot from it. Thank you for your professional guidance.

Wang Fang, regarding the scheduling during the advanced training course at the end of the month, I have preliminarily discussed it with Teacher Li Wei. We need to coordinate with you on the specific handover time. Are you available this afternoon?

Teacher Li, regarding the scheduling during the training program at the end of the month, I have had a preliminary discussion with Wang Fang. I will organize the specific handover plan and report it to you later.

Head Nurse Wu Min, this afternoon, the daughter of the patient with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) specially delivered a handwritten thank-you letter filled with many encouraging words. This recognition from the patient deeply moved me and gave me a deeper understanding of the value of this profession. Thank you for your usual guidance and support.

Me: Mom, I've adjusted the font size of the family health handbook according to your and Dad's suggestions. It's finalized and sent to your email. Please take a look when you have time, and print it out to keep at home.

Dear Night Shift Doctor,  

The patients in beds 3, 5, and 7 under my care are stable today, and their vital signs have been recorded. Bed 3 will be discharged tomorrow, and all the discharge documents and medication prescriptions have been completed and placed at the nursing station. Please note that for Bed 5, Mr. Zhang, he should get up slowly at night, and I have reminded him to turn on the light. Thank you for your hard work.
Mom, I finished dinner and drove home. The traffic was smooth. What did you and Dad have for dinner? It's cold outside, so please keep warm.

Mom, Dad, I'm home. I've sent the final version of the health handbook for the community that I mentioned earlier to your WeChat. Please take a look when you have time. How about we have a video chat at 20:40?
Ms. Li, the results of the re-examination ECG for the patient in bed 3 mentioned during the morning meeting are now available and have been uploaded to the system. Please review them.
Mom, it's Christmas Eve today. I'll be having dinner with my colleagues tonight and will be home late, so don't wait for me to eat.
Jingjing, I just finished my English class at noon, and the foreign teacher praised me for my improvement! How are you spending Christmas Eve?
Jingjing, I picked a gardenia-scented candle for you, hope you like it! See you at the gathering tomorrow!
Weiwei, I'm almost there, which court are you at?
Brother Tao, sorry, I already have plans for tomorrow night. Have a great time! Let's make plans another time.
Alright, understood! Let's plan for next time then. Merry Christmas!
Mom, Merry Christmas! It's busy at the hospital today, and I have a colleague gathering in the evening, so I might be home late. Did you and Dad have dumplings?
Jingjing, Merry Christmas! How was work today? Are you free tonight? I'd like to discuss something with you.
Wang Fang, I have already prepared the discharge summary and medication instructions for Grandpa Li in bed 3. Could you please review them? If everything is fine, I will submit them.

【Zhengzhou Central Hospital】Dear Dr. Yu Xiaowen, the latest issue of the European Heart Journal that you subscribed to is now available online. The theme is "New Advances in the Diagnosis and Treatment of HFpEF." Click the link to view: http://t.cn/XXXXX. Reply T to unsubscribe.
Brother Feng, Merry Christmas! Have you and Sister-in-law received the nut gift box I sent? It's quite cold in Zhengzhou today. How's the weather over there in Shenzhen?

Jingjing, I'm going to attend a training session in another city next week, which will take about three days. I was wondering if you could help me take care of Orange. I've already prepared the cat food and cat litter and left them at home. Would that be convenient for you? I can bring you the key on whichever evening works best for you.
Me: Nana, I'll arrive at Zhenghong City around 19:05. Have you guys arrived yet?
Zhang Jing: We're all here, in the 'Naples' private room, waiting for you!
Mom, I had spicy soup for breakfast at our usual spot today, and it still tastes as good as ever. Have you and Dad eaten yet?

Jingjing, thank you again for the scented candle! Regarding the care of Orange next week, I've made a list: the cat food is 'Ocean Star' adult cat food, a small handful each morning and evening; the treats are 'Inaba' cat sticks, at most one per day; the litter box should be cleaned daily, and water must be available at all times. He likes to sleep on the sofa cushions at night. Please take note of these details. We'll meet at 7 PM on Sunday evening!

Mom, I just finished reading a book about the history of medicine. It contains many stories related to our daily experiences with seeing doctors and taking medicine, which is quite interesting. How have you and Dad been lately? Please stay warm in this cold weather.

Mom, I'm up and just finished breakfast. Today's training schedule is quite packed, with group discussions in the morning and a presentation in the afternoon. Thank you and Dad for the birthday wishes. Let's talk more tonight.
Jingjing, I've come to Zhengzhou for training. Even on my birthday today, I have to attend classes. The training center here has a nice environment, but it's a bit cold. How have you been lately?
Dr. Zhao, thank you for having lunch together. I really enjoyed our conversation. Let's do our best for the afternoon presentation!

Me: Mom, I just left the training center and am driving back to the hospital now. The evening rush hour is a bit congested, so I estimate I'll arrive around 6:30. I'll have dinner at home tonight, so no need to wait for me.
Me: I've placed the order for takeout, sweet and sour pork and birthday noodles. It's expected to be delivered home by 19:20. I'll be home around 19:25, just in time to eat.
Mom, I finished my training this morning, had lunch with colleagues at noon, will go to Jingjing's house to pick up Juzi in the afternoon, and will be home for dinner in the evening.

【XX Pet Hospital】Dear member, your appointment for the annual health check-up package for 'Orange' has been confirmed. The scheduled time is 3:00 PM on January 5th. Please bring your pet to the hospital on time. Reply TD to unsubscribe.

Me: Jingjing, I'm home, and the oranges are all settled. The dinner gathering is at 17:40 in the 'Chunhua' private room of Qingyue Fusion Restaurant, right? I plan to leave around 17:00. What about you guys?
Zhang Jing: Yes, yes, that's the private room! I've already made plans with Yueyue, Fangfang, and Weiwei. We'll probably arrive around that time too. See you tonight, birthday girl!
Teacher Li, I have arrived at the hospital and am currently changing into my white coat. I will see you in the office shortly.
Mom, it's New Year's Eve today. Are we making dumplings at home tonight? I'll head back right after work.
Dear colleagues, Happy New Year! Thank you for your support and assistance over the past year. Wishing you all good health, smooth work, and a happy family in 2026!
Jingjing, Happy New Year! Thank you for being such a close friend by my side over the past year. Wishing you continued beauty and happiness in the new year, and may our friendship last forever!
Me: Alright, let's go with the place you picked. We'll pack up after breakfast and head out. The homestay owner said the road isn't hard to navigate.

Dear Consultant Wang, I am Yu Xiaowen. Thank you for the interview this morning. Regarding the plan to adjust the monthly savings to that dedicated account, I have understood it. I will start implementing it from next month. If there are any new market analyses in the future, please feel free to share them with me at any time.

Hello Ms. Yu, I'm Xiao Wang from Lianjia. The viewing arrangement for tomorrow has been planned. We'll meet at the subway entrance at 9 a.m. The property you're particularly interested in for the day after tomorrow has also been confirmed for viewing, scheduled for 2 p.m. I'll send you the specific address and important details shortly.
Xiaowen, let's meet at our usual spot in the cafeteria tomorrow at noon. I have something I'd like to get your opinion on.
While reading on the balcony in the morning, the chirping of birds was particularly clear, and the sound of vehicles passing by in the distance could be heard, making me feel very relaxed.

Zhang Lei: Xiaowen, please supplement the details of the meeting tasks: We need to retrospectively process 200 medical records of hospitalized hypertension patients. Please plan the steps as soon as possible.

Dear Nurse Yu, I am the daughter of Aunt Li in bed 8. Thanks so much for your help last night. My mother is feeling much better today and her mood has stabilized. Once again, thank you for your timely assistance and patience!

Xiaowen, please remember to start preparing the discharge assessment for that patient with chronic heart failure after the meeting, and complete it independently. Submit it to me before the morning handover tomorrow.
Yu Xiaowen: Today's lunch break was quite engaging in the music group chat. We compared several recorded versions of that symphony with the pastoral title, which was quite enlightening.

Good morning, Teacher Li. I focused on practicing patient enrollment in the test environment and completed the simulated case operations. However, I am unclear about the logic for filling in the concomitant medication field in the baseline data entry section, and I would like to consult with you about it later.
I'm here, at the window seat in the restaurant.

Yu Jianguo: Xiaowen, have we brought all the ingredients we bought today—the bamboo leaves, glutinous rice, Xinjiang dates, and the candied dates you love? We'll start wrapping them as soon as we get back.
summarized_info: Received a text message from my father, asking if I had brought all the ingredients for making zongzi that were purchased today. The message specifically mentioned bamboo leaves, glutinous rice, Xinjiang red dates, and candied dates.

message_content: Su Ya: Xiao Wen, have you finished firing that thing you made this afternoon? How did it turn out? My little vase seems to have come out quite well.
Xiaowen, let's meet at 15:00 this afternoon at our usual spot, "Qinghe Light Meal," for a drink after exercising.
I've arrived and am waiting for you at Court 3 in the badminton hall.
Su Ya: Hi Xiaowen, this is Su Ya from the pottery class. I'll bring some leaf pattern references for the afternoon practice session, and we can study them together.
Dr. Yu, I am Zhang Ming, a family member of the patient. I have sent you a handwritten letter today to express my gratitude.

Hello, I'm the customer who bought kitten supplies and asked a lot of questions at your store the afternoon before yesterday. Thank you for your patient answers at that time—my kitten is now in stable condition! I'd like to ask, besides that store, are there any other places where I can purchase the goat milk powder you recommended?
Lin Wei: I'm waiting for you at the stadium in the Olympic Sports Center, hurry up.

Teacher Zheng, thank you for your guidance! The exhibition has ended, and the works have been brought back. This exhibition experience has given me a deeper understanding of creation. When you have time next week, I will come to learn new vessel forms from you.
Wang Fang: Xiaowen, I've already ordered sweet and sour pork tenderloin. Take a look at the menu and add some more dishes.
Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, have you been busy lately? It seems from your social media that your rotation in the cardiology department has been quite fulfilling.

Yu Xiaowen: Yeah, I just finished my first independent night shift. It was exhausting, but I learned a lot. By the way, my brother video-called me a few days ago and said he was also completely worn out.
Zhang Jing: What's up with Brother Feng? Is his gaming company working on another big project?

Yu Xiaowen: Well, their team was working on a new game that was almost ready to launch, but during testing, they discovered a major bug. It's said that if not handled properly, all player data could be lost.

Yu Xiaowen: My brother and his entire team worked overtime for a week, staying up late every night, and finally managed to patch the vulnerabilities before the deadline. He said he feels nauseous just looking at code now, but at least the project can be launched on schedule, which is a relief.
Master Zheng: Xiaowen, the plain teacup you made in the last class has dried in the shade. You can come to glaze it this weekend. Do you have any initial ideas about the glaze color?
Yu Xiaowen: Hello, Teacher Zheng! I've been thinking about this lately. Personally, I don't really like colors that are too bold or flashy; I feel they don't match my personality.
Yu Xiaowen: I've seen some senior students in the studio making celadon-like cups, which are very elegant. However, I feel that the solid color is a bit too "quiet" and lacks a bit of fun.

Yu Xiaowen: I find that I particularly like the glaze colors you previously fired, the ones with rock textures and wood grain patterns, like the gray-white gradients or brown-yellow transitions. They feel very natural, serene, and have details worth savoring. I’m wondering if my first piece would be suitable for trying this style?

Master Zheng: Your intuition is excellent. The glaze that mimics natural textures indeed requires some skill to control the flow and crystallization, but it suits the tone you're aiming for—serene yet rich in detail. We can start by experimenting with the glaze that imitates bluestone patterns this weekend.
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, Nana just finished video chatting with me, and she seems completely exhausted lately.
Yu Xiaowen: Huh? What happened to her? Is the work pressure in Shenzhen really that intense?
Zhang Jing: Yeah, she mentioned that her product team had been working overtime for a whole month to meet the deadline for launching a new feature module, and they were practically exhausted.
Yu Xiaowen: Oh my god, that's really pushing it. But with Nana's strong abilities, she should be fine, right?

Zhang Jing: Well, she said although it was tiring, it was quite fulfilling. The feature was successfully launched, and the big boss praised their team by name during the regular meeting, also giving them a decent project bonus. There was a sense of pride in her tone.
Zheng Guodong: Xiaowen, before next week's class, you can think about what type of work you'd like to try next.

Yu Xiaowen: Hello, Teacher Zheng. I’ve always enjoyed making small items that can be used in daily life, such as teacups or small bowls for fruit. It feels particularly satisfying to create something that I can actually use myself.

Zheng Guodong: This direction is excellent; utilitarian ware is the foundation of pottery. So, do you have any preferences in decorative styles? I noticed that the few bisque-fired pieces you made earlier have a quite consistent style.

Yu Xiaowen: Well, I don't really like anything too flashy or in particularly bright colors. I prefer matte finishes with quiet, understated hues, like off-white, light gray, or pale cyan. As for decorations, maybe just a few simple engraved lines or some hand-pinched marks—it feels more natural that way.

Zheng Guodong: Understood. This "wabi-sabi" or minimalist style indeed requires a good feel for the material and an understanding of the clay's properties. In the next class, we can focus on practicing the matte glaze ratios and line-carving techniques you prefer.
Today at the studio, I tried making a teacup with leaf texture, but the throwing was uneven and the glaze color got ruined during firing, so I'm in a bad mood.
Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, Nana seems to be in a low mood lately.
Yu Xiaowen: What's wrong? Hasn't she always been quite driven?

Zhang Jing: Well, there was an internal competition for a project management position at her company. She had prepared for a long time, but in the end, she wasn't selected. It seems she's quite discouraged and a bit confused about what to do next.
Yu Xiaowen: Sigh, the competition pressure in Shenzhen is indeed intense. Let's find a time to have a video chat with her in the group, to offer some comfort and guidance.
Sun Yue: Xiaowen, do you still listen to classical music to relax after work lately? Any new discoveries you can recommend to me?
Yu Xiaowen: Yes, my taste has changed a bit recently. I used to like the Romantic period, but now I'm fascinated by Baroque music.
Sun Yue: Baroque? Like Vivaldi's "Four Seasons"?

Yu Xiaowen: "The Four Seasons" is also great, but I've been particularly fond of Bach lately. His "Goldberg Variations" or "Brandenburg Concertos" are both structurally rigorous and filled with a rational beauty, which helps me quickly calm down after a hectic day at work.
Sun Yue: Wow, that sounds really advanced. I'll give it a try later and see if it can cure my restlessness.
Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, I just finished a video call with Nana, and things are really tough for her over there.
Yu Xiaowen: Huh? What's wrong? Did something happen in Shenzhen?
Zhang Jing: The apartment she rented, the neighbor upstairs was renovating, and somehow they ended up breaking a water pipe. Water gushed down and completely seeped into her living room.
Yu Xiaowen: Oh my god, is everyone okay? Was there a lot of property damage?

Zhang Jing: Everyone is fine, but the living room took the hit. She said that rug is basically ruined, and a small side cabinet against the wall got soaked at the bottom and is a bit warped—she’s heartbroken about it. Right now, she’s in the middle of negotiating compensation with the landlord and the upstairs neighbor.
Wang Fang: Xiaowen, the background music from that meditation app you recommended last time is quite good. What kind of music do you usually listen to for relaxation? Still classical music?
Yu Xiaowen: Well, it's mostly classical. But recently, the style I've been listening to has changed a bit.
Wang Fang: Oh? From the romanticists you used to like, what have you switched to now?

Yu Xiaowen: I'm catching up on the Classical period. I've found that Mozart's piano concertos are especially perfect for listening to after work. The melodies are so beautiful, like the second movement of K.467—they can instantly clear all the clutter from your mind and are incredibly relaxing.
Wang Fang: Haha, that sounds very sophisticated. I'll give it a try later. It's much more relaxed than Beethoven's "fate knocking at the door," right?
Jingjing, shall we meet at the usual place tomorrow at 4 p.m.? We need to thoroughly review the two apartments we saw today. Still at that Starbucks.
Yu Xiaowen, I heard the simulated teaching part of today's BLS assessment was quite challenging. How did you perform?
Chen Siyu: Xiaowen, are you busy? Let me share a funny story that recently happened in our class—it left me both laughing and crying.
Yu Xiaowen: Just got off work, not busy. What's the fun story? Tell me quickly, let me have a laugh too.
Chen Siyu: While grading the weekly journals, I came across the notebook of a usually very introverted boy. Guess what he wrote? He actually wrote a "Character Observation Report" about me!

Chen Siyu: It recorded that I usually arrive at school around 7:20 in the morning, enjoy drinking Luckin Coffee's latte, have a habit of using red chalk to highlight key points when writing on the blackboard, and unconsciously spin my pen when feeling irritable... It was written in such detail.
Yu Xiaowen: Hahaha, that's quite the observation! How do you feel?

Chen Siyu: At first, I felt a bit offended, as if my privacy had been intruded upon. But on second thought, this child observes things so meticulously—perhaps they have the makings of a writer or journalist—and I found it quite interesting. I’m still thinking about how to talk to them about this matter.
Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, my boyfriend has been playing a game called Cyberpunk 2077 lately. The graphics and story seem pretty amazing. Are you interested in this kind of game?
Yu Xiaowen: I've heard of it, but I've never played it. Honestly, I'm not really into games that are purely about fighting and killing or those that require particularly high skill levels.
Zhang Jing: So what kind do you like? Surely you don’t enjoy those simulation games where you’re constantly treating patients, do you? [chuckle]
Yu Xiaowen: Of course not! Isn't work tiring enough [facepalm]. I prefer games that I can immerse myself in, with well-told stories and richly developed characters.

Yu Xiaowen: For example, the world view is grand, each character has their own background and motivations, the choices you make in the game genuinely influence the direction and outcome of the story, and you even have to face moral dilemmas without standard answers. Playing this kind of game feels more like reading an interactive novel or participating in a movie.

Zhang Jing: Got it, you like the kind that's both mind-bending and heartfelt. Sounds more interesting than just slashing monsters. Next time you come across a good game like that, recommend it to me—I'll give it a try too!
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, Nana seems to be having a hard time finding a place to rent recently. The rent in Shenzhen is really shocking.
Yu Xiaowen: Yes, she mentioned in the group chat yesterday that she looked at several apartments but wasn't satisfied with any of them. They were either too expensive or too far from the company.
Zhang Jing: She just sent me a private message saying she finally got it sorted! She rented a studio apartment in the Technology Park through an agency.
Yu Xiaowen: That's great! How much is the rent? What are the conditions?

Zhang Jing: The monthly rent is 6,500 yuan. She said it hurts a bit, but the location and layout are decent. It comes with a small private balcony and a simple kitchen where she can occasionally cook. Finally settled down.
Wang Fang: Xiaowen, do you have any good podcast recommendations for the commute after work lately? I'm tired of the one I've been listening to.
Yu Xiaowen: I haven't been listening to podcasts lately; I've picked up classical music again. I've discovered a treasure that's perfect for quiet evenings.
Wang Fang: Oh? Which master's? I still prefer something with more melody; overly complex music is tiring to listen to.

Yu Xiaowen: Bach's Cello Suites. With just a single cello, the sound is particularly serene and powerful, capable of quickly calming one down. I often listen to it before bed lately, and I feel it helps me relax more than the piano pieces I used to listen to.
Wang Fang: That sounds so advanced! I'll give it a try. Are there any recommended versions?
【Zhengzhou Central Hospital Pharmacy】Medication Pick-up Notice: Please collect your medication at the pharmacy window on the 1st floor using code A2868. Details are subject to the pick-up slip.
Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, I really enjoyed our heart-to-heart talk at the café today. Let's confirm: we'll update each other on our study progress every Sunday evening, okay?
Sun Yue: Xiaowen, have you heard? Zhao Ming is going to change jobs!
Yu Xiaowen: Huh? I haven't heard about that. Wasn't he doing well at Shenzhen People's Hospital? Where did he jump to?

Sun Yue: I just saw it in our class group chat. There's a private hospital in Shenzhen, quite large in scale, offering a position for a deputy chief physician in neurosurgery. The compensation and career development opportunities are both very attractive.
Yu Xiaowen: Wow, an associate chief physician—that's a big step up. Has he made up his mind?

Sun Yue: Well, he privately messaged me saying he has already accepted the offer and is currently going through the resignation process. Moving from a public to a private institution is quite a challenge, but he mentioned wanting to try out a different platform.
Zhang Jing: Have you been under a lot of stress lately? I noticed you’ve been sharing some pretty soothing music on your social media.
Yu Xiaowen: Not bad, just need some sounds that can calm me down. Lately, I've been looping Dvořák's "From the New World."
Zhang Jing: The Ninth Symphony? I seem to have some impression of it. Is there a particularly famous melody?

Yu Xiaowen: Yes, exactly ninth. My favorite is the second movement, Largo. The nostalgic theme played by the English horn always soothes my heart whenever I listen to it—so serene, yet tinged with a hint of melancholy.
Zhang Jing: After hearing you say that, I really want to find it and listen to it. It seems your taste has been quite "classical" lately.
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, are you busy? I just finished a video call with Nana, and she seems really down.
Yu Xiaowen: Just got off the night shift, what's up? What happened to Nana?

Zhang Jing: She has been leading the team to work on that new APP project for nearly half a year. It was originally scheduled for internal testing this week, but it was halted by a phone call from the big boss this morning, citing a need for strategic adjustments.
Yu Xiaowen: Huh? So sudden. She must be really upset, having put in so much effort.

Zhang Jing: Yes, she said she felt particularly frustrated, like punching cotton, and the team morale was also affected. I told her to put it aside for now, adjust her mindset, and wait for the company's new arrangements.
Wang Fang: Xiaowen, are you off work yet? I'm completely exhausted today. What kind of music do you usually listen to for relaxation?
Yu Xiaowen: Just got home. I'm still the same, mostly listening to classical music—it helps me calm down.
Wang Fang: Classical music, it seems so elegant. Do you have any favorite pieces or instruments?

Yu Xiaowen: I've been really into the cello lately. I feel its tone is particularly deep and warm, giving a sense of embracing everything, especially during solos, where the emotional expression is incredibly delicate.
Wang Fang: The cello, like Yo-Yo Ma's? It sounds very soothing. I'll give it a try sometime.
Me: Jingjing, thank you for the guidance the other day. I feel much better now. Whenever I'm exhausted from duty, I remember what you said: 'Just get through it, and everything will be fine.'
Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, are you free this weekend? A new Yunnan restaurant just opened, and I heard their rice noodles are super authentic!
Yu Xiaowen: Great! I can finally catch my breath this week. My brother just finished his busy period too, and he had it really rough before.
Zhang Jing: What's wrong with Brother Feng? Did you stay up late coding again?

Yu Xiaowen: Yeah, their team has a major project about to launch, but the core module suddenly got stuck, and performance just wouldn't improve. He's been working overtime for three days straight and is practically exhausted.
Zhang Jing: Oh my, that sounds overwhelming. How did you manage to sort it out later?

Yu Xiaowen: Fortunately, their team was capable. Together, they reorganized the algorithm logic and optimized several versions, finally completing it before the deadline. He said that although it was exhausting, seeing the results go live gave him a great sense of accomplishment.
Wang Fang: Xiaowen, my commute has been so boring lately. Do you have any good podcast recommendations?
Yu Xiaowen: Highly recommend "Stops at Every Station"! I've been listening to it during my commute and while doing pottery lately, absolutely love it.
Wang Fang: That's an interesting name. What is it about? Is it about travel?

Yu Xiaowen: Not exactly. Each episode invites a guest, who could be an architect, botanist, intangible cultural heritage artisan, or even an astronaut trainer! Listening to them share stories and insights from their fields really broadens your horizons.
Wang Fang: Wow, it sounds like high quality! How long is it? I sometimes only have fragmented time.

Yu Xiaowen: Each episode is about 40 minutes to an hour, and I usually listen to it in two sessions. But the content is really substantial, and after listening, I feel the time was well spent. It’s much more rewarding than just listening to music or funny anecdotes.
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, are you free this weekend? I heard that a new Yunnan cuisine restaurant has opened in Zhenghong City. Would you like to go and try it?
Yu Xiaowen: Sure, I should be free on Saturday afternoon. I've been a bit tired lately and would like to relax.
Zhang Jing: What's wrong? Is the hospital very busy lately?

Yu Xiaowen: Not too bad, just the usual work. The main thing is my brother; he's been having some trouble with a project in Shenzhen recently and vented to me about it, so I've been a bit worried too.
Zhang Jing: What's wrong with Brother Feng? He's so capable, how could he run into trouble?

Yu Xiaowen: He said that a fairly important project their team was responsible for was almost ready to launch, but then they discovered a particularly hidden bug. It took them a long time to figure out that it was a compatibility issue with a third-party library they were using. To locate and fix this bug, the entire team worked overtime for three consecutive days, staying up late into the night each time.
Zhang Jing: Oh my, that sounds incredibly stressful. But was it resolved in the end?

Yu Xiaowen: Well, it's resolved. After identifying the root cause, we switched to a different approach to work around it. He told me yesterday that he can finally leave work on time now, but he's completely exhausted. It seems like these sudden, intense battles are just the norm in the internet industry.
Sun Yue: Xiaowen, how is your preparation for the attending physician exam going recently? Are you under a lot of pressure?
Yu Xiaowen: There's definitely pressure, having to study for a few hours every day after work. But I have my own secret to relieving stress.
Sun Yue: What secret? Share it quickly, I need it too. Our pediatrics department has been extremely busy lately.

Yu Xiaowen: I still listen to classical music. However, I've noticed that my taste has changed a bit recently. I used to prefer music with a strict structure, but now I'm particularly fascinated by Debussy's hazy, watercolor-like piano pieces.
Sun Yue: Debussy? Is he the French composer who wrote "Clair de Lune"?

Yu Xiaowen: Yes, that's him. His impressionist works, such as "Clair de Lune" and "The Girl with the Flaxen Hair," don't have the clear melodic lines of traditional classical music. Instead, they resemble flowing light, shadow, and color.

Yu Xiaowen: When I come home from work every day, exhausted and mentally drained, I put on a Debussy piano album, dim the lights, and let my mind go blank. That hazy, floating sensation really helps me detach from the intense, precise medical mindset of the day, allowing my nerves to truly unwind. It works better for me now than listening to Bach or Mozart.
Sun Yue: That sounds like a very sophisticated way to relax! I want to try it too. Please share your playlist with me!
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, Nana just finished video chatting with me, and she's feeling a bit down.
Yu Xiaowen: What's wrong? Is the work pressure too much?

Zhang Jing: Yes, the product project she had poured her heart and soul into for over half a year was almost ready to launch. However, for some strategic reasons, the senior management at the headquarters in Shenzhen abruptly called it off.
Yu Xiaowen: Oh my god, this must be a huge blow to her. But fortunately, it's just the project being suspended, not a problem with her personal abilities. Let's comfort her more.
Zhang Jing: Well, I've already made arrangements with her. She'll take some time off next month and return to Zhengzhou, so the three of us can get together properly and relax.
Wang Fang: Xiaowen, could you share the playlist from that music app you mentioned last time? I'd like to listen to some quiet music during my shift.
Yu Xiaowen: Sure, I recently created a new playlist called "Afternoon Contemplation" and I'd like to share it with you.
Wang Fang: Got it! Let me see... Wow, it's all Mozart and Haydn, and many of them are string quartets? Didn't you used to prefer symphonies?

Yu Xiaowen: Yes, my taste has changed a bit. Lately, I’ve found chamber music from the Classical period particularly captivating, especially string quartets. The way the different parts intertwine creates both a sense of dialogue and harmony. Unlike symphonies, which are grander, it’s more suitable for quiet listening alone—perfect as background music while doing pottery or reading.
Wang Fang: Got it, that's what you call "refined enjoyment." I'll give it a try; maybe I can cultivate a bit of artistic flair, haha.
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, is there any news from Nana? She said the results would be out today.
Yu Xiaowen: Just got in touch! She said the results are out, and she passed the internal competition for the position at the company in Shenzhen!
Zhang Jing: That's fantastic! I knew she could do it! What's the specific position? Still a product manager?
Yu Xiaowen: No, I got promoted! I'm now the Product Director. She said the competition was quite intense, with several senior managers vying for the position.
Zhang Jing: Director! That's amazing! She's the fastest among the three of us. When she gets back, she definitely has to treat us to a big meal!
Wang Fang: Xiaowen, what have you been listening to on your way home from work lately? Still those piano pieces?
Yu Xiaowen: Well, I've been listening to more classical music lately. But my taste has changed a bit. I used to listen to Mozart and Bach more often, finding their structures well-organized.
Wang Fang: Oh? So what kind of music do you like listening to now?

Yu Xiaowen: I've been particularly fascinated by works from the Romantic period lately, such as Chopin's nocturnes and Schumann's piano suites. They feel more emotionally rich, with freer and more lyrical melodies, which helps relieve work stress.
Wang Fang: Sounds very advanced! I'll give it a try later. But don't you listen to Debussy's impressionist style? It's also very atmospheric.
Yu Xiaowen: I occasionally listen to 20th-century music as well, but my recent favorite is still the Romantic period. It feels more relatable.
Xiaowen, the results of today's case discussion meeting are out, and the department has decided to recommend you to attend an important conference in Beijing. We'll discuss the details later.
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, are you free this weekend? I found a newly opened bookstore with a fantastic atmosphere. Want to go check it out together?
Yu Xiaowen: Great! I happen to have this weekend off. By the way, let me tell you something—my pottery class instructor, Master Zheng, has been really impressive lately.
Zhang Jing: Oh? What's up with Master Zheng? Has he developed some new glaze color again?
Yu Xiaowen: It's even more impressive than that. He went back to his hometown, Jingdezhen, last month to attend a national ceramic art exchange exhibition. And guess what happened?
Yu Xiaowen: The wood-fired tea set he brought, which integrates modern design concepts, actually won the "Craft Innovation Award"! Our class group chat is buzzing with everyone congratulating him.
Yu Xiaofeng: Sis, have you been busy lately? It's getting colder here in Shenzhen. How about you in Zhengzhou?
Yu Xiaowen: Brother, I'm doing okay, just a bit tired from the rotation. It's also cold in Zhengzhou, but I've developed a habit of morning running, and I actually feel more energetic after it.
Yu Xiaofeng: Sure! Do you listen to music while running? Or is it your classical music?
Yu Xiaowen: I do, but I've noticed my listening habits have changed. I used to enjoy listening to a complete symphony at home, like Beethoven or Brahms, and really immerse myself in it.

Yu Xiaowen: But when I run, the rhythm of those large-scale compositions just doesn't feel right. I recently created a special morning running playlist, which includes piano pieces like Chopin's Nocturnes and Schubert's Impromptus, or fragments of Mendelssohn's String Octet. The melodies are beautiful, the rhythm is gentle and steady, perfectly matching the breathing pace of running, and it helps the mind relax.
Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, I just finished a video call with Nana. She's really been in high spirits lately!
Yu Xiaowen: Really? What's the latest news from Shenzhen? With her ENTJ personality, she must have pulled off some major project again.

Zhang Jing: You guessed it! There's a very important product line within their company that's about to launch a new project. Several teams were competing for it, and she and her team had been preparing for months. Their proposal was particularly outstanding. I just heard the result—she won it!

Yu Xiaowen: Wow, I'm really happy for her! Although it's completely different from my routine of ward rounds and writing medical records, it sounds exciting just hearing you talk about it. She's probably going to be even busier now.

Zhang Jing: Yeah, she said she’ll be fully devoted to this project for the next six months. But looking at her, she seems tired yet happy. When she returns to Luoyang for the Spring Festival, she’ll have to treat us to a nice meal!

Wang Fang: Xiaowen, the white noise app you recommended last time is somewhat useful for me when writing medical records, but it gets monotonous after a while. What do you usually listen to when you're reading or doing pottery?

Yu Xiaowen: As for me, I still have the same old habit of listening to classical music. But lately, I've found that string quartets from the Classical period are particularly suitable as background music.
Wang Fang: String quartet? Could you be more specific? Haydn? Mozart?

Yu Xiaowen: Yes, it's theirs. The structure is clear, the melody is beautiful, but it doesn't overflow with emotion like Romantic music, nor is it as complex and brain-burning as Baroque. Like background wallpaper, it calms me down without disturbing my thoughts. Mozart's K.465 and Haydn's "Lark" Quartet—I've been listening to them on repeat lately.
Wang Fang: Got it, I'll go search for a "Classical String Quartet" playlist on a music app right now. Thanks for the recommendation!
Liu Qiang: Xiaowen, regarding the patient with chest pain awaiting diagnosis from yesterday, the ECG shows abnormalities. We need to discuss the treatment plan.
Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, have you been in touch with Sisi lately? It seems like she's got something going on!

Wang Fang: Xiaowen, the sleep playlist you recommended last time was really helpful for me! Have you discovered any good music lately?

Yu Xiaowen: Yes! My preference for classical music has shifted a bit recently. I used to particularly enjoy Mozart's fresh and lively style, but now I'm more fascinated by the emotionally intense and structurally grand works from the mid to late Romantic period.
Wang Fang: For example? I don't understand at all, please explain.

Yu Xiaowen: Like Tchaikovsky's "Pathétique Symphony" and Mahler's Fifth Symphony. When I listen to them after a tiring day at work, I feel that all those complex emotions are expressed through the music, which actually provides a sense of release. Baroque music is too structured, and 20th-century music feels a bit too avant-garde for me—I haven't quite developed an appreciation for it yet.
Wang Fang: Got it, you like those with a lot of drama and rich emotions! I'll give it a try later. Gotta go now, a patient is calling.
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, Nana just had a video call with me and seemed particularly down.

Yu Xiaowen: Haha, that's a classic piece for calming the mind. My taste has changed a bit recently, and I've started to get into more grand and profound things.
Wang Fang: Oh? For example?

Yu Xiaowen: Like the symphonies of Mahler and Bruckner. Especially after work, when I'm home alone, listening to that kind of grand structure and complex emotions that build up layer by layer feels particularly effective for releasing stress, although sometimes it can be quite depressing.
Wang Fang: That sounds profound! Late Romantic period, right? I might need to listen to Mozart for a few more years before I can keep up with you.

Zhang Jing: Xiaowen, Nana just video called me, and she seemed a bit down.

Master Zheng: Oh? That saber isn't cheap and requires maintenance. Why are you interested in it?

Yu Xiaowen: I feel it's completely different from machine-made steel knives. Although not as hard, it has a unique elasticity when used. When trimming clay, it feels like you can sense the thickness variations in every part of the body, with very delicate feedback. Although a bit more expensive, I want to invest in a tool that can accompany me for a long time and has a sense of "dialogue."

Master Zheng: Haha, it seems you’ve truly started to get the hang of it, beginning to pursue "hand feel" and "feedback." This kind of perception is very important in pottery. That knife was forged by an old friend of mine, and the quality is indeed excellent. If you decide you want it, I’ll help you ask about it.

Zhang Jing: Wenwen, Nana has been really upset lately. The water pipe in her upstairs neighbor's apartment in Shenzhen burst, and the water seeped down, soaking the ceilings and walls in her living room and bedroom. There are large water stains and even mold spots.
Yu Xiaowen: Huh? That serious! What did the landlord and property management say? Who will cover the repair costs?

Zhang Jing: Nana immediately contacted the property management, who then got in touch with the upstairs neighbor. At first, the neighbor tried to shift the blame, suggesting it might be due to the aging of the building. Later, the property management investigated and confirmed it was an issue with their water pipe. Nana was quite firm in her stance, communicating with the neighbor using photos and videos as evidence. In the end, the neighbor admitted responsibility and agreed to cover all the repair and repainting costs.
Yu Xiaowen: That's good. Nana is still so decisive in handling things. But where has she been staying during this time?

Zhang Jing: She mentioned that her company happened to have a short-term closed project during those days, so she stayed at a hotel near the office. It turned out to be a blessing in disguise, as she avoided the disturbance from the renovation. Now the house has been repaired, and she has just moved back in.

Zheng Guodong: Xiaowen, the series concept about "resilience of life" you mentioned last time is very good. Regarding the glaze colors, do you have any initial ideas? Are you thinking of trying some more unconventional colors, or continuing with your previous style?

Yu Xiaowen: Hello, Teacher Zheng. I've thought it over carefully and still feel that using overly bright or high-tech colors isn't quite suitable. I've realized that I've always had a preference for matte textures, and in terms of colors, I lean toward earthy tones like soil, rocks, or withered leaves. Ideally, they should also carry a bit of the naturally formed, uneven gradients and textures that emerge during the firing process. I feel that this kind of color palette better expresses the sense of calm and inner strength I want to convey.

Zheng Guodong: Hmm, this direction is clear and aligns well with your personality and the theme. A matte earth-toned color palette, pursuing natural textures and subtle variations. I have a few glazes on hand that might meet your requirements. For example, there’s a matte glaze called "Autumn Mountain Brown," which produces an effect similar to weathered stone surfaces after firing. There’s also one called "Moss Green," a matte green with a gray undertone and gradations of depth. I can bring samples for you to try in the next class.

Yu Xiaowen: That's wonderful! Thank you, Teacher Zheng. "Autumn Mountain Brown" and "Moss Green" sound so evocative—exactly the kind of tones I was hoping for. I'm looking forward to trying the glazes in the next class!
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, are you free this weekend? It's been a while since we last went for a city walk together. I heard there are some nice new cafes near the Erqi Tower.
Yu Xiaowen: Jingjing, I might not be available this weekend because I have to work. Besides, my brother seems to be quite busy in Shenzhen lately; I just finished a video call with my mom.
Zhang Jing: What are you up to, Brother Feng? Working on another big project?

Yu Xiaowen: Yeah, their team has recently been bidding on a smart healthcare system project, and it seems they just secured it, so he's been working overtime lately. My mom is even worried about his health.
Zhang Jing: Wow, impressive! Will there be any collaboration between this project and your hospital in the future? Brother Feng is really crossing boundaries to support healthcare.
Wang Fang: Xiaowen, you must be tired from the night shift! I just got off surgery and I'm exhausted. How do you usually relax after work? I feel like I need some background music.

Yu Xiaowen: Fangfang, you've worked hard too! When I go home, I enjoy doing pottery while listening to classical music—it really helps me relax. Lately, I’ve been captivated by Chopin's nocturnes and waltzes. I feel his melodies are exceptionally delicate and can soothe the day's irritations.
Wang Fang: Chopin! That sounds very sophisticated. I usually just listen to pop music. Are there any recommended albums or performers? I'd like to give it a try.

Yu Xiaowen: You can start by listening to Rubinstein's complete collection of Chopin nocturnes, which is considered a classic version. Recently, I've been listening to the recordings by Polish pianist Zimerman, and I feel the emotional expression is more modern.
Xiaowen, the slender neck part you made in today's pottery class is so exquisite. Teacher Zheng also said your technique has improved!
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, have you been in touch with Sisi recently? I heard she seems to be in a low mood.
Yu Xiaowen: Well, we had a phone call last week. She was indeed feeling a bit down; she broke up with her boyfriend of two years.
Zhang Jing: Huh? Really? I remember they had a pretty good relationship. How did they suddenly break up?

Yu Xiaowen: According to Sisi, the main disagreement was about future plans. The man wanted to return to his hometown to develop, while Sisi still wanted to stay in Luoyang to work as a teacher. Neither was willing to compromise, so they parted ways amicably.
Zhang Jing: Sigh, long-distance relationships and career direction issues are indeed tough. Let's comfort her more and accompany her to relax next time we return to Luoyang.

Wang Fang: Xiaowen, last time you mentioned you've been under a lot of stress lately and rely on listening to music to relax at night. Are you still listening to those classical pieces? Any new discoveries you'd recommend?

Yu Xiaowen: Yes, classical music is still my "mental stabilizer." Recently, I've been particularly fascinated by Debussy. His "Clair de Lune" and "Prélude à l'après-midi d'un faune" seem tailor-made for late-night solitude.
Wang Fang: Debussy? The one from the Impressionist movement? That sounds so sophisticated. I usually just listen to pop songs, haha. What's special about his music?

Yu Xiaowen: Yes, exactly, Impressionism. His music has a particularly strong sense of color. Unlike Beethoven, which is filled with dramatic conflict, Debussy's work is more like a flowing, hazy painting that allows you to completely detach from the tension of the day. When I come home from work now, I make a cup of tea and play some Debussy—it's the most healing moment of my day.
Wang Fang: I'm totally sold by your recommendation! I'll go check it out too, maybe it can cure my insomnia. Thanks for the suggestion!
Zhang Jing: Wenwen, Nana just finished a video call with me, and she's feeling a bit down.
Yu Xiaowen: What's wrong? Is the work pressure too much?
Zhang Jing: Yes, she started overseeing a new project at the end of last year and has recently been conducting pilot promotions in Shenzhen.
Zhang Jing: The user feedback data fell far short of expectations, and the internal team review meeting left her feeling overwhelmed. Now she has to readjust the plan, and the pressure is immense.
Yu Xiaowen: Sigh, the pace of the internet industry is just too fast. Let's comfort her more in the group chat over the weekend.
Zheng Guodong: Dr. Yu, Happy New Year. The pottery class plan for the new year is out. Which advanced course direction are you more interested in?

Yu Xiaowen: Happy New Year, Teacher Zheng! I recently visited a Jun porcelain exhibition at the museum and was particularly fascinated by the kiln transformation effect, often described as "one color entering the kiln, myriad colors emerging."

Yu Xiaowen: I was thinking, it would be quite interesting if we could apply the unique glaze color variations of our Henan Jun porcelain to modern designs of everyday items like teacups and vases. It would blend traditional charm with practicality.

Zheng Guodong: This is a great idea! Combining the characteristics of local kilns with modern design is a very valuable creative direction. I happen to have relevant glaze materials and firing techniques that I can teach you.

Teacher Zheng: Xiaowen, today's 'Support' piece is very well done! The posture of the three pillars vividly captures the resilience and sense of support needed in the process of growth. Looking forward to you putting the finishing touches on this series.
